ul.li: Call stack is live data that is used to print a callstack
OVERVIEW
information about a function call, called a call frame, is pushed and popped onto the stack while the program is running
occasionally a snapshot is taken
more often than not, thrown
frequently some try/catch block will catch
when caught, one of a few things may happen. later.
To help us think about call stacks, here is a short example
Apple calls banana, which calls coconut, which does some dangerous-looking math.
Inception?
One way we can visualize the call stack is like this
Clojure call stacks are Java call stacks
Java call stacks have one frame per Java method call
Many, but not all, Clojure function calls are a single Java method call
Sometimes Clojure calls (multimethods, var, seq, apply, etc.) generate a couple Java call frames
Not even all Java method calls in Clojure are just one frame, if runtime reflection is used (insufficiently hinted)
Final note, message passing (sending to an agent or remote host) may feel like a call and logically be a transfer of control, but loses the call stack
Finally, divide is called. Now if it happens to be a zero, divide will?
Before it can throw the exception, it has to create one
Has a message and snapshot, and can now be thrown, unwind, pop the stack repeatedly, carrying the unchanging exception with it.
A try/catch block may catch, at which point 3 options. One option is to rethrow the exception
Looks like this. After catch, decide it you want to rethrow, then do so. As if you never caught it. Same, unchanged exception.
Another option is to chain a new exception onto the one you caught. Looks like this:
Done to change the type of the exception, perhaps because of Java checked exceptions
Or done to create a different message describing the exception
Or inadvertently throw without chaining the caught exception
Note new message often includes the old one
Funny thing: banana appears in each exception, once when calling coconut (pushing), and once when creating the new Exception (popping). Different line numbers. Both appear in most stack traces.
Ignore completely?
Respond programmatically?
In order to talk about more stack traces, we need a more complex example.
Some use of apply
Recursive (coconut calls apple)
Chaining
Lets look at the anatomy of a standard Java stack trace
Pay attention to signal vs. noise
Backwards causes
Reduce noise by summarizing instead of repeating frames
Though in a confusing way
Aleady have done better. Here's a shorter trace of the same exception.
This was printed by pst, introduced in Clojure 1.3
several options, but by default only prints root cause
loses wrapped exceptions - very bad for compiler exceptions
So compiler exceptions are detected and printed differently.
So it starts with the final cause
Critical filename and line number printed (slime doesn't print this)
More of the stack trace is printed, but frequently not useful
There are many other stack printing libraries, various features and tradeoffs. But I want to talk about a new alternative.
Even smaller printout yet, so as long as what is missing is noise, it's a win.
- Convert snapshot to Clojure data
- Fix the order of causes
- Filter out redundant cause messages
- Filter out low-signal call frames
- Clean up Clojure function names
- Column layout so eye can follow related info
- Replaceable print function
This is where I promised we would go, right?
- We've got the cause chain as data
- Sending across threads loses stack
- Snapshot before send
- In new thread, catch any exception
- Splice the two together for printing (repeat forward across call)
This is Longbottom
The town of Longbottom was where the Shire's most famous tobacco was harvested. From there is was distributed widely, perhaps smuggled even as far as Isengard.
This library provides tools for harvesting stack traces and smuggling them to other threads or even as far as other hosts.
Middle lines catch and print any exception.
Bottom code smuggles and splices. Note the smuggle message.
(send (agent :foo) (lb/smuggling-fn* inc "my agent send"))
Prints like this. Looks a bit like a cause, but there's your smuggle message.
So, we did better! less noise, more signal
